ce of non-Irish immigrants in Celtic-Tiger and post-Celtic-Tiger Ireland. The book assembles an international group of 18 leading and prestigious academics in the field of Irish studies from both sides of the Atlantic, including Declan Kiberd, Anne Fogarty and Maureen T. Reddy, amongst others. Key areas of discussion are: what does it mean to be ‘multicultural’ and what are the implications of this condition for contemporary Irish writers? How has literature in Ireland responded to inward migration? Have Irish writers reflected in their work (either explicitly or implicitly) the existence of migrant communities in Ireland? If so, are elements of Irish traditional culture and community maintained or transformed? What is the social and political efficacy of these intercultural artistic visions?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCultural pluralism in literature. 0aEnglish literaturexIrish authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aImmigrants in literature. 0aIrish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aIrish literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aCeltic-Tiger Ireland.  aImmigration.  aIrish literature.  aLiterary criticism.  aMulticulturalism.  aTransculturality.1 aArmstrong, Charles I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalzano, Wanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEstévez-Saá, Margarita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFogarty, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v